For the first time this year, this course explains to students the need to adopt good sleep habits to improve their school and physical performance, as well as their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and Director General of Health Services at the University, said that the university had decided to introduce the course after finding that students had a serious lack of sleep during the week.
The course time consists of different interactive exercises.
One of the sections presents the image of a dormitory containing different objects (coffee fees, curtains, basketballs, books...) on which students click to know the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on their physical benefits and the importance of integrating a routine before bedtime.
In another section, participants learn how the lack of long-term sleep can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
A map of the campus with interactive icons then invites participants to reflect on their daily routine.
"We know that this will not instantly change the behavior of students.
However, we believe they have the right to know this information - in the same way you have the right to know what the effects of smoking on health is," added Professor Czeisler.
According to him, the culture of pride of " spending a white night" still exists, and he adds that modern technology and the growing pressure exerted on students constantly make sleepiness a growing problem.
Having enough sleep and good quality should be the "secret weapon" of students to fight stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said - even to avoid weight gain, because lack of sleep puts the brain in mode of innation, making them constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student in chemistry and physics, helped Professor Czeisler design this course after being one of his students last year, during his first year at Harvard.
He claimed that this course had opened his eyes and moved him to insist that it be offered throughout the campus.
He hoped that the next step would be to propose to all third-cycle students to follow a similar curriculum before joining the renowned institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students predict an alarm as well for bedtime as for awakening, and be aware of the adverse effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED light, which can disrupt their circadian rhythm and cause sleeping disorders.
