New research in an area of the Scottish Highlands seeks to reveal how bats use the landscape in their quest for food.
It is hoped that the observations will shed new light on the behaviour of these single flying mammals and will guide future conservation activities.
The study of the National Trust for Scotland will follow common bats and sopranos as well as long-eared brown bats and Daubenton in the Inverewe Garden in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed at key locations around the property to monitor the activity of bats throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies using portable detectors.
A professional sound analysis will determine the frequency of bats and the activities of different species.
A map and a report on habitat will be prepared to provide a detailed picture of their behaviour across the territory.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor for the NTS, hopes that the results will reveal the most important habitat areas for bats and how they are used by each of these species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work such as prairies and the best way to preserve forests for bats and other associated species.
In Scotland and the United Kingdom, the population of bats has declined considerably over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects perchours and leads to loss of habitat.
Windmills and lighting can also represent a risk, as well as the kill-mock paper and some chemical treatments of construction materials, as well as the company cat attacks.
The bats aren't really blind.
However, given their nightly hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to identify insects and obstacles to their flight route.
In charge of the protection of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 large gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, the NTS takes bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts, who regularly conduct surveys, perchatory inspections and sometimes rescues.
The organization also established the first and only reserve of bats of Scotland on the site of Thrave in Dumfries-et-Gallow, which houses eight of the ten species of bats of Scotland.
David Thompson, domain manager, says the site is the ideal territory for them.
