"We have old buildings, lots of old trees and all the good habitat.
But there is still much to learn about bats, so the work we do here and in other places will help us to understand better what bats need to thrive."
It stresses the importance of verifying the presence of bats before maintaining the properties, because by destroying it without wanting a single maternity nest, it is possible to cause the death of 400 female and small, or even the disappearance of an entire local population.
The bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, to disturb them, or to destroy their perchoirs.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish head of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
